segments.text: It was easy to defend that base.
It was a real good base to be on at any time of year.
That was our main base of operation.
We spent half our time probably there, but it was a good base to be at because it was so secure and they had bean shoes there.
And that's some of the things that

people want to see the movies, probably don't realize that when you get all of a sudden to be in a place where you can completely get used to, at the futures, you know, at the clubs, you know, you go back, you know, and stuff, and yet, you know, the next day you put back on a shop or go somewhere that, you know, just completely opposite.
So...
The main base has been pretty well protected.
It's just that they could always hit them with rockets or mortars, except for the podium channel I made on, like I said.
Supposedly, I read about it again, but that one was a good base to be on.
So how much slot time did you have?
Oh, probably about half the time we were there.
It was not on any type of direct operation.
And then, even when you're on an operation,
As I said, you know, a lot of it turned out to be not productive from a military standpoint.
So overall, it wasn't like that was a day of conflict and a day of threat.
It wasn't like that.
From my point of view, it wasn't as bad as, I'm sure, on the radio, it's not on the radio like this.
Again, a lot worse, a lot more often.
Did you know anybody that was like that, that had that?
Oh, yeah.
Some of my friends.
One of the things I had to do in high school when I came to the first one in my class, they would kill me.
I was very young.
I had to get a telephone out there.
As a matter of fact, while I was training in Florida to go over, I had 12 home attempts.
I had to take care of the children.
So, yeah.
Six or nine of my classmates in that class were about 190 kids.
Six of them were killed.
How has all of this affected your life now?
Overall, I probably came more personally out of it than come out of it.
I just think I have a really good chance of people in terms of life in general.
I just have great appreciation for the things that you have done for me.
I honestly, I don't, I wasn't scarred, but I know physically, so I don't know if I can have a good impact on people.
But obviously, I would recommend that everybody has to do their own work to better their own person.
I've heard, I've heard,
So how do you feel about, say, the typical portrayal of the Vietnam vet who came home and went crazy, who's shooting people and...
That's probably, you know, an exaggeration.
I mean, I'm sure it is something that happens, but I don't think everybody should perceive it, you know, that there's a lot of time, a lot of pressure, you know, and killing.
But like I say, I'm sure that people have had experiences that were a lot more severe.

you know, that they probably does have some of that impact on, you see, I was fortunate that the combat encounters that I did have were a lot less public and severe to what some of these people were trying to throw me.
We had casualties, but I had to deal with the chaos and everything that goes around.
It's just hiding him.
He just doesn't know what he can do in a situation like that.
Until the minute something happens, you don't know how it's going to affect you overall.
When I first came back, I didn't know what I was going to do.
I didn't know what I was going to do.
There are a few that it has happened to.
It looks like the worst case.
So how did you deal with the fear of the band?
It's hard to explain.
Just, again, I think that's everybody.
It's different.
I believe that people ever just completely freeze and they couldn't do anything.
Others just take the strength and others arrive and it's just like, I think that's part of the strength.
When they're seeing you still operate, you just kind of keep doing it.
So what did you do after you came back?
Well, I had another 10 months in the service, so I finished that and then I went back for general entry.
And shortly thereafter, I got married to my wife.
I had known her prior to going to Vietnam.
But obviously, they wanted me to get married or anything like that.
But we had no marriage.
And I had to do that.
So I got married.
Let's see.
It didn't take much after I got out of the service.
As long as two years after it's back to being nominated, I'll get married.
You know, and then get several different jobs, and then finally get to work for Exxon.
That's my plan.
So does your wife think you changed from before you went to Indiana?
Anybody ever comment to you about that?
Some of the people I think that knew me a little better.
At that time I didn't know her.
I didn't know her all that long before I went to Vietnam.
Somebody I had met was stationed with her brother in the service and met her.
before I went over, but we were just dating for a fairly short time.
And with being in the service, I didn't see her that often, so she always felt that I changed significantly before, after.
Some people I knew as a friend said, you know, they had seen some changes.
I think it was just the changes that were more serious and just things in general, how it ended.
life, but no matter changes.
Anything else you'd like to say for the record?
Like I said, I'm sure everybody has their own experiences and gains and losses from it, so it's, you know, everybody.
I don't know if there's anything else.
I have been real quiet about the whole situation, but I never did talk to him about it.
Would you do it again?
I probably wouldn't.
You know, now it's funny, as I get older, it's hard not to.
My son would ask me that question.
You know, if I knew the outcome was going to be the same, I would.
And if I really had the same convictions at the time, I would.
I mean, if I felt that we were doing, you know, something that needed to be done for the people there.
Because like I said, at the time, I had the same, I had the strong convictions.
So I probably would if I think if I...
I had the same involvement or knowledge I have now about that particular war.

I would probably try not to get as involved with it as I was then because I just feel like we didn't have the full commitment to that country or those people that we should have if we were really trying to help.
So how do you feel about the military?
Would you want your son to be in the military?
Do you have a good feeling about that?
Yeah, in a way, I think it's a good experience.
It helps you handle a lot of situations.
There's a lot of good training and discipline and training where you get to know your own person.
So I think it can be a real learning experience.
It does have a lot of good training.
And of course, you know, when there's an actual war involved in it, the whole experience is completely different.

So, um, but it was, uh, I don't know how you ever can justify a war, but basically, so, um, you know, now, we'd like to see everything done, everything, everything, the situation resolved without a war, because it's, it seems such a futile thing, no matter who shot you in the eye.
I mean, it does seem like a good evidence out of it, but it's hard to say for sure what happens there.
Well, would you ever want to go back to Vietnam?
Yeah, actually.
To see what happens?
Yeah, I would.
I told my wife about it.
The country itself is a beautiful country.
You know, we operated in the Central Coastal Leagues and the Central Highlands.

I mean, it's just, it is a land, a beautiful country, and sometimes when I look at the scrapbook and the pictures and stuff, you wonder about the people in the villages that are taking pictures of what they're doing and how they're doing it.
He'd never know who they are because he don't think he didn't know their names.
Yeah, I've always felt that I'd like to see it again.
I tried to watch the show, but then it wasn't shown until I was in Canadian.
So I had to go back and report on it.
I'd like to do it again.
That's it.
Thank you.
Thank you.
Okay, well, on through with that.
